NARRATIVE:
On July 22, 2023, at approximately 2102 hours I, Trooper First Class Graves #7199, was dispatched to 7570 Fentral Avenue, Salisbury Wicomico County Maryland 21801 for a possible shots fired. Upon my arrival to the scene I made contact with the complainants who I would identify as Nakisha Banks (1/F DOB:01/15/1981), Nyquez Banks (1/M DOB:07/26/2006) and Kaniya Bratten (1/F DOB:03/10/2010).

While speaking with the victims all three would inform me they were laying down for bed when they had heard loud bangs/gun shots from the front of the residence and afterwards had immediately called 911.

Troopers conducted neighborhood checks and would speak with neighbors in the surrounding area -
Fentral Avenue:
7574- Male Subject identified as Douglas Brown (1/M DOB:11/10/1967) advised house cameras facing away from crime scene, heard the gun fire but did not observe anything.
7564- 1/Female advised she did not observe anything, heard the gun shots, but house does not have cameras.
7558- No answer at the residence, does have cameras (unknown if operational)

Brent Avenue:
7562- - 1/Male advised he did not observe anything, heard the gun shots, but house does not have cameras.
7559- - 1/Female advised she did not observe anything, did not heard the gun shots and house does not have cameras.

Upon further observation of the crime scene I would observe approximately 3 bullet holes on the front face of the residence. I would also observe one hole in the rear windshield of the vehicle parked in the driveway of the residence (a black Hyundai Sonata bearing Maryland registration 6ED4307). Inside the vehicle I would observe a fist-sized rock resting in the backseat/trunk area.

While continuing my observations of the crime scene I would observe that a bullet appeared to have traveled through a wood pillar of the front porch, the front glass window (now shattered), the front wooden door, struck an outlet in the living room and the bullet was observed resting on the floor of the living room near the front door.

A bullet hole was also located in the bedroom window of Kaniya’s bedroom, the bullet appeared to have traveled through the window, the bedroom wall and into another door of a closet in the residence.I would also observe a bullet hole next to the bullet hole of the glass door/wood door area. In total 3 bullet holes on the face of the residence were located.Troopers on scene would also locate a single handgun bullet casing in the grass area approximately 10 feet from the rear of the vehicle in the driveway.

All occupants remained in the living room area and crime scene tape was placed around the house. During the course of investigation Kaniya's father would arrive on scene, later identified as Keonte Bratten Sr. (1/M DOB:05/05/1989) to check on the condition of Kaniya and then would leave shortly after. 

Due to the circumstances of this incident I requested both Criminal Enforcement Division and Crime Scene Tech to respond to the location for further investigation.

Crime Scene Tech responded to the scene at approximately 2206 to collect evidence and photographs of the scene. 

Criminal Enforcement Division responded to the scene at approximately 2242 hours to conduct further investigation. 

I request this case be forwarded to CED for further investigation

All events occurred in Wicomico County Maryland.

On 07/23/2023, I responded to 7566 Buckman Avenue to assist CED with a search warrant/warrant servic.

I arrived on scene with CED and STATE. Contact was made at the front door. The subject identified as "Bryant Thomas Brown-Clark (B/M 10/19/2006)" was inside the residence. Brown-Clark was identified as the suspect in the attempted shooting/murder the day before at 7570 Fentral Avenue. Brown-Clark was detained and transported to the MSP Salisbury Barrack for further questioning. Search warrant was executed at 7566 Buckman Avenue. Brown-Clark was then transported to WCDC without incident later that day and charged accordingly.

Form 112 completed.

All events occurred in Wicomico County, Maryland.

This case is closed.

Narrative:
    On 7/22/23 at 2102 hours, I, M/Tpr. A. Edwards, was dispatched to 7570 Fentral Ave, Salisbury, Wicomico County, MD 21801 for a report of shots fired into a residence.  When I arrived on scene, I initially positioned by vehicle in a manner to prevent any further traffic from traveling on Fentral Ave to preserve any possible evidence in or around the roadway.  I made contact with TFC Wilkins and TFC Graves who had arrived on scene prior to me and was advised the residence had been struck by several bullets and the rear window a vehicle that was parked in the driveway was able broken.  I immediately observed the glass of the front exterior door of the residence to be shattered with a large amount of glass on the porch and on the door sill.  I observed a bullet hole in the lower portion of the front storm door and was advised by the homeowner that the bullet had traveled through the door and struck an electrical outlet along the wall immediately behind the door.  It appeared that the bullet had fallen to the floor right below the outlet. I observed an additional bullet hole in a bedroom window that was to the left of the front door. TFC Wilkins was able to locate one bullet casing in the front yard of the residence near a tree. I marked the casing with a note card in order to keep it from being disturbed or moved.

    I observed the damage to the vehicle in the driveway and believed it was not from a bullet hole.  There was a large hole approximately two inches in diameter in the middle of the window. I looked through the glass and observed what appeared to be a piece of a brick that was approximately the same size as the hole in the glass. I entered the residence and entered the bedroom in which the bullet had entered the window.  I was able to observe a hole in the rear bedroom wall at a similar height to the bullet hole in the window.  It appeared that the bullet had traveled through the bedroom wall and traveled into the hallway where it traveled through a closet door and into a large plastic bag in the closet. I did not remove the plastic bag in order to preserve evidence that would be later processed by crime scene technicians.  I briefly spoke with the homeowner, Nakisha Banks and she advised that her son was friends with a juvenile who had recently been murdered a few weeks earlier.  Banks advised that she believed that could be the only reason that someone would want to shot at her residence.  She was unable to confirm any of that information and advised that her son or daughter were not involved in any illegal activity that would have lead to the shooting.  I advised Banks that criminal investigators and crime scene technicians were en route to the residence to conduct the investigation and that investigators would conduct a more detailed interview with her when they arrived.  

    Based on the nature of the incident, I complete two MSP form 78 (Consent to Search and Seize) forms with Banks for her residence and vehicle in order to process them and collect evidence related to the crimes. Banks gave written and verbal consent for her residence and her vehicle.  I provided the consent for to TFC Mingos.

    Once investigators from the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region and crime scene technicians from the Maryland State Police Forensic Sciences Division arrived on scene, I maintained security of the scene security until the vehicle and residence were processed for any evidence.

    I request this case remain open pending further investigation by criminal investigators.
CASE OPEN.

On July 22, 2023, at approximately 2102 hours, [9:02 p.m.], Troopers with the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack responded to 7570 Fentral Avenue, Salisbury, Wicomico County, Maryland 21801 for a report of shots fired. Upon arrival, Troopers made contact with the victim(s), Nakisha Banks, DOB: 1-15-1981, Nyquez Banks, DOB: 7-2-2006, and Kaniya Bratten, DOB: 3-10-2010, [hereinafter referred to as Nakisha, Nyquez and Kaniya].

     According to Nakisha, Nyquez and Kaniya had just turned in to go to bed when they heard loud bangs/gunshots from the front of the residence. They immediately called 911. Due to the nature of the incident the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region were notified and assumed the investigation.

     Upon arrival, Investigators observed that a bullet appeared to have traveled through a wood pillar of the front porch, the front glass door, the front wooden door, struck an outlet in the living room and the bullet was observed resting on the floor of the living room near the front door. Investigators also observed that the rear windshield of the victim's vehicle, black Hyundai Sonata, had a hole in the rear windshield. Located inside the vehicle was a large rock. A single 9mm shell casing was located in the grass area approximately 10 feet from the rear of the vehicle in the driveway. A bullet hole was also located in the bedroom window of Kaniya's bedroom. The bullet appeared to have traveled through the window, the bedroom wall and a closet door inside the residence.

     Investigators learned while speaking with Kaniya that her brother, Karontez Bratten, DOB: 2-28-2007, [hereinafter referred to as Karontez] received a text message via Instagram at approximately 1700 hours, [5:00 p.m.] on July 22, 2023 from Instagram account "hittafrmupdaway" that said he was going to shoot up his house where Kaniya lives.

     Investigators made contact with Karontez who identified the Instagram user as Bryant Thomas Brown-Clark, DOB: 10-19-2006, [hereinafter referred to as Bryant]. Karontez told investigators that there has been tension between him and Bryant as a result of other shootings which have occurred recently in the Salisbury, Maryland area.

     While on scene, Kaniya viewed a live stream video via Instagram from Instagram account "hittafrmupdaway", previously identified as Bryant's account, that portrayed Bryant utilizing a cellular device to live stream video of Bryant flashing what appeared to be a barrel of a semi-automatic handgun. Bryant also made comments during the video about the shooting which stated, "Dumbass got your little sister's house shot up after that dissn shit." "I got to look outside to see how many cops out here." A second live stream video was provided to investigators by Kaniya from Instagram account "hittafrmupdaway" which stated "that twelve (12) stormin the block." "mother fuckers stormin this bitch that fast." Investigators noted that a female's voice in the live stream video is heard calling the name "Bryant" and Bryant responds to the female in the video.
     Kaniya told investigators that Bryant lives around the corner and was able to show investigators his residence, located at 7566 Buckman Avenue, Salisbury, Maryland 21801 which would explain why Bryant was able to observe police response to Kaniya's residence. Kaniya further advised that Karontez and Bryant used to play basketball together in the neighborhood.

     Investigators authored a search and seizure warrant for Bryant's residence located at 7566 Buckman Avenue in Salisbury. On July 23, 2023 at approximately 0832 hours [8:32 a.m.], MSP S.T.A.T.E. Team made entry via knock and announce into the residence without incident. Investigators conducted a search of the residence which was met with negative results for the seizure of evidence pertinent to the investigation. Bryant was placed under arrest at the scene and transported to the MSP Salisbury Barrack for processing. All juvenile laws and procedures were followed per MSP policy.

     Upon leaving Bryant's residence, investigators responded to Kaniya's residence for a follow up interview. Kaniya provided investigators with an Instagram photo from Instagram account "hittafrmupdaway". The picture appears to have been taken from inside Bryant's bedroom which depicts the Maryland State Police armored vehicle being operated by the MSP S.T.A.T.E. Team upon their arrival to the residence.

     Investigators have preserved all social media accounts pertinent to the investigation. Bryant is being charged as an adult for attempted murder and other related charges. Department of Juvenile Services has been notified and made aware of Bryant's status. Troopers from the MSP Salisbury Barrack transported Bryant to the Wicomico County Detention Center for processing.

     Detailed supplements will be added reference interviews that were conducted. Instagram warrants will be obtained along with Geo-fence warrants.

     Case closed by arrest, investigation continuing.

Initial Interviews with victims on scene:
     On July 22, 2023 at 2257 hours, I, S/TPR Mingos, arrived on scene at 7570 Fentral Avenue, Salisbury, Wicomico County, Maryland 21801, and made contact with victim(s) identified as, Nakisha Banks, DOB: 1-15-1981, Nyquez Banks, DOB: 7-2-2006, and Kaniya Bratten, DOB: 3-10-2010, [hereinafter referred to as Nakisha, Nyquez and Kaniya] for an initial interview. The following interview was audibly recorded and is documented below:
  • Victims advised that no one was injured during the shooting.
  • Nakisha identified as mother of Kaniya and Nyquez
  • Nyquez and Kaniya are juvenile victims who reside in the residence that was just penetrated with bullets.
  • Nyquez stated he was sitting in front of the window on the right side of the residence as if you were staring at the residence from the road.
  • Nyquez stated the shots were heard around 9:05 P.M.
  • Kaniya stated she was sitting in her room which is the front of the house, closest window to the front door entrance.
  • Nakisha stated she was sitting in her bedroom which is the back-right bedroom which is located on the other side of the residence staring from the front entrance to the residence.
  • I asked, “Does anybody know who it is that did this.”
  • Kaniya proceeded to show me the first video of an Instagram live feed video identified by Instagram username "hittafrmupdaway".
  • Nakisha stated someone sent her the video to her on her phone.
  • I asked the victims, “Does this voice sound familiar?”
  • Nakisha stated, “yes.”
  • I asked, “Who is this voice to you?”
  • Nakisha and Kaniya stated the voice is nothing to them but they know who it is and he [suspect] lives the next street over and he [suspect] is familiar with [victims] house.
  • Nakisha stated, “Karontez Bratten, is her [Kaniya’s] brother. The one he [suspect] was after. He [suspect] thought he lived here.”
  • Nakisha stated Korontez Bratten does not live at this residence.
  • Nakisha stated suspect must have gone live on Instagram app and Nakisha’s friend sent it to her through text message.
  • I asked, “Does anyone know the boys name who lives up the road?”
  • Nakisha stated, “Bryant Clark.”
  • Nakisha stated Bryant Clark is about 16 to 17 years old, black male.
  • Nakisha stated she believes the target tonight was Kniya’s brother [Korontez Bratten], who is also known by Instagram screen/username “lorr__tez”.             
  • Nakisha stated you can hear the suspect mention “lorr__tez” in the video post.
  • Kaniya stated, “He [Bryant] knows that’s my window.”
  • I asked, “Why do you think he [Bryant] did that? Why is he [suspect] after “lorr__tez”?”
  • Nakisha stated, “I don’t know, I think they had words I guess, today.”
  • I asked, “How old is “lorr__tez”?”
  • Nakisha stated he is about 15 or 16 years old.
  • Nakisha stated, “That is what he [Bryant] says in the video, you come up on my block…...and 12 hear that fast.”
  • Nakisha stated she observed a brick that was inside her vehicle that was thrown through the back windshield. Nakisha stated she did not go into her vehicle at any point.
  • Nakisha stated when he [suspect] shot through the house, one of the bullets hit the socket that was hooked up to her surveillance camera and she was unable to recover any surveillance from the shooting.        
End of initial interview___________________________________________________________

Initial Instagram evidence provided by victims:

First Video File Name: RPReplay-Final1690074526:
Video Description:  1 minute and 13 second run time which starts out as male voice stating, “ewww dam, (pause) dam, (video buffers for a few seconds), that’s 12 storming the block, lorr__tez shit got blew up!” In the background you can hear a female voice yell, “Bryant!”. Male voice in the video says, “huh?” Female voice continues to speak which is undecipherable. Male voice in video responds back to female voice saying, “I don't know, Bryant didn’t do shit, I just (male voice stops speaking for a couple seconds).”  Male voice then states. “Dam, the mother fucking cops storming that bitch that fast!?” Male voice continues saying, “What the fuck, Dam!” Male voice says, “I told niggas to move off my block man!” (video continues but breaks up for a few seconds). Male voice states, “The cops be around I'm go get in the house.” Male voice continues, “Niggas be talking that shit on the live earlier, what happened? What just happened lorr__tez!?” End of video.

Note: During the beginning of the live feed video, it appears to be displaying the side of a blue wall with gray paint markings on the wall and part of a tv. A pop up on the video comes up that captions “request to be in this live video” with two unidentified accounts trying to view the video. The rest of the video goes black. You can hear the male go outside but the video appears to stay dark. After the conclusion of the residential search warrant, the wall markings in the first video shown by investigators on scene match the same wall markings observed in the search warrant photos of Bryant Thomas Brown- Clarks room appeared to be the same.

Second Video File Name: RpReplay-Final160074677
Video Description: 32 second run time which starts out as a males voice stating, “Bitch Nigga, I’m spending every fucking day.” In the video, you can observe a barrel of what appears to be a handgun which goes in and out of the video briefly. The males voice appears to be stating, “That shit aint happen nigga, you were just on the live, your dumbass got your little sister and fucking tossed her house shot up during that dumbass dissin shit, bitch!” The male voice continues to say, “I just dropped my shit.” (You can hear in the background of the video that something dropped, possibly the handgun which was displayed in the video earlier.) Male voice states, “Imma go look to see how many more cops are down there.” You can hear what sounds like a door opening and the video ends.

Note: During the video, it appears the camera is on the ground facing towards the ceiling. It is assumed this is the angle because you can see a television that is turned on. You can also tell this is a live feed video because other Instagram users are joining the video and it states at the bottom, “16 others joined.”

Instagram Image File Name: 3321.jpg
Image description: The image displays a still shot from an inside window of a residence. You can observe in the picture it is through a window due to the reflection of the blinds inside the window. You can also observe the Maryland State Police S.T.A.T.E Team black bear cat (armored vehicle) outside a residence. The photo is captioned “crazyyyyy” across the middle of the photo.

Note: After the residential search warrant, it was observed that this photo was taken from Bryant’s bedroom during the execution of the residential search warrant by MSP S.T.A.T.E. Team. I know this to be Bryant’s bedroom due to Bryant’s parents advising that is Bryant’s bedroom during the execution of the warrant. The angle from Bryant’s bedroom also matched with the angle of the image capture and the position of where the bear cat was positioned during the execution of the warrant.

Case remains closed based on arrest. Investigation continues pending investigative supplements to be added.

On Friday, August 18, 2023, at approximately 1000 hours [10:00 a.m.] I Sgt. Kaniya's mother, Nakisha Banks [hereinafter referred to as Nakisha] answered my call and I explained my reason for wanting to speak with Karontez.  Nakisha telephoned Kaniya while I was still on the phone who then made contact with Karontez.   While speaking with Nakisha I could hear Karontez say that he received my text message, and he already talked to the police the night of the incident.  Karontez told Nakisha that he was accused of being a snitch and had received threats as a result of this investigation and his involvement.  Karontez told Nakisha that he would contact me after he was done with football practice.

Narrative:

On August 22, 2023, I Sgt. Donna Radcliff, #5640 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region responded to 7610 Fentral Avenue, Salisbury, Wicomico County, Maryland for a follow-up interview with the residents at that address.  Upon arrival, I made contact with Patricia Cannon [hereinafter referred to as Cannon]. My interaction with Cannon was audibly and visually recorded utilizing my agency issued body worn camera.  Patricia advised the following:
  • Patricia lives on Fentral Avenue near where the incident occurred
  • Patricia was familiar with what happened and stated that "rumors" are saying that "PJ" put Bryant up to shooting the house up that night.  "PJ" is approximately 27 years old and lives in the neighborhood.
  • According to Patricia, she heard that "PJ" told Bryant prior to the incident to "do what he has to do".
  • Patricia could not/would not provide the identities of where this information originated from.  
  • Patricia's son, "Boo", was not at home.  Patricia would not give us "Boo's" contact information or his full name.
  • Patricia advised her neighbor across the street has cameras, however, she does not believe that they are working.
  • I was able to confirm with the neighbor across the street he has cameras, however, they are not operational.
  • Patricia was unable to provide any additional pertinent information.
Case closed by arrest

Narrative:

On August 22, 2023, I Sgt. Donna Radcliff, #5640 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region responded to 7550 Brent Avenue, Salisbury, Maryland 21801 as part of a follow-up to this investigation. Upon arrival, I made contact with Jarrica Banks [hereinafter referred to as Jarrica].  This interview was audibly and visually recorded utilizing my agency issued body worn camera.  Below is a synopsis of the interview and not a transcript, therefore some paraphrasing may be used:
  • My contact with Jarrica was to determine "PJ's" location and speak with the juvenile that resides at the aforementioned address.
  • Jarrica identified her husband William Hinman as "PJ", however, Jarrica denied that William Hinman could have had anything to do with the shooting on Fentral Avenue.
  • Jarrica confirmed that she had a juvenile son, approximately ten (10) years of age and agreed to allow me to speak to him concerning the investigation.
  • Jarrica's son, Brenden Hinman, [hereinafter referred to as Brenden] advised that on the night of the shooting he was outside his residence on Brent Avenue letting his dog in the house, when he observed Bryant Brown-Clark [hereinafter referred to as Bryant] walking in the street in front of his residence.  It should be noted that Brenden is familiar with Bryant due to his interaction with Bryant in the neighborhood.
  • Brenden and his sister were home alone when Bryant walked past Brenden's residence.
  • As Bryant walked by he told Brenden to go in the house.  Brendan said okay and stated that he was going back inside anyway.
  • Brenden said it was dark outside when he saw Bryant. He was unable to make out what Bryant was wearing and added that he did not observe him carrying anything in his hands because he was not paying attention.
  • Brenden said a few minutes later, when he was in the shower, he heard gunshots.
  • Upon leaving Jarrica's residence, I learned that William Hinman is not the "PJ" that is being implicated in the shooting.
  • I further learned that "PJ" resides at 28106 Rockawalkin Ridge Road, Salisbury, Maryland and the rumor that he is involved originated from Bryant's mother, Danielle.
Case closed by arrest.

Narrative:

On August 22, 2023, I Sgt. Donna Radcliff, #5640 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region responded to 28106 Rockawalkin Ridge Road, Salisbury, Maryland  21801 for a follow-up interview to this investigation.  Upon arrival, I made contact with Ronald Morgan, Jr. [hereinafter referred to as Ronald].  This interview was audibly and visually recorded utilizing my agency issued body worn camera.  Below is  synopsis of the interview and not a transcript, therefore some paraphrasing may be used.
  • Ronald is uncle to the victim, Kaniya Bratten [hereinafter referred to as Kaniya.
  • Ronald's nickname is "PJ".
  • Ronald was aware that his name had been implicated in the investigation and was told by Kaniya that law enforcement would probably want to speak with him.
  • Ronald knows Bryant Brown-Clark [hereinafter referred to as Bryant] from the neighborhood.
  • Ronald advised that on the night of the incident he was at a family gathering and received a call from Kaniya telling him that her house had been shot up. It was not until he talked with Kaniya that he became aware that Bryant had something to do with the shooting.
  • Ronald denied that Bryant had discussed what he was going to do and further added that Bryant normally confides in Ronald, seeking advice and guidance at times.
  • Ronald said he tries to be a role model for the younger kids in the neighborhood and that Bryant's mom, Danielle, is mad at him because she believes Bryant is Ronald's responsibility.
  • Ronald was aware that Danielle was spreading rumors that he had something to do with the shooting.
